{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4fbf3f13-4629-44df-98bf-aaee0b88cb96","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the breakdown:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed **test ID computation** — IDs now incorporate the fully-qualified type name differently. Azure DevOps matches history by test ID, so every test looks \"new.\" This is cosmetic; history will rebuild going forward. There's no workaround to reconnect old history.\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` and `[AssemblyInitialize]` is **no longer associated with a specific test** (which makes sense — class init runs once before all tests). Accessing `TestName` now throws.\n\nYour fix for `SetupTests.cs` — guard or remove the access:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_NTEJa3HxfJEaclJIwkGssC","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-ae5bb0f46148415a8790cc7b5c217e5b/SetupTests.cs","old_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        var testName = context.TestName;\n        // Log setup for specific test\n    }","new_str":"    [ClassInitialize]\n    public static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n    {\n        // MSTest v4: TestContext in [ClassInitialize] is not test-specific,\n        // so TestName is unavailable. Use class-level info instead.\n        var className = context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName;\n        // Log setup for class\n    }"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-ae5bb0f46148415a8790cc7b5c217e5b/SetupTests.cs."}],"interactionId":"446fb723-57e3-4315-bb04-4ac943c450c9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a comprehensive answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Test ID computation changed** — MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed (fully qualified names now include assembly), which is why Azure DevOps sees them as \"new\" tests with no history.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize/AssemblyInitialize** — In v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` and `[AssemblyInitialize]` no longer has test-specific properties like `TestName`. \n\nSince class and assembly initialization runs before any individual test executes, properties like `TestName` aren't available and will throw an exception—this is an intentional design fix. Beyond that, there are several other breaking changes to be aware of: default test parallelization behavior may differ, `DeploymentItem` attributes work differently, `DataRow` attributes have changed, and some deprecated APIs have been removed entirely.\n\nLooking at the code issue, the problem is on line 13 where `context.TestName` is being accessed inside a `[ClassInitialize]` method—\n\nthis will fail in v4 since the context at the class level isn't tied to any specific test.","outputTokens":779,"requestId":"E3C2:1ED62C:1D28812:20C5914:6A053F21"},"id":"c4127cb4-1a40-4af7-b465-aa506b7cfe1b","timestamp":"2026-05-14T03:19:13.297Z","parentId":"03640f17-52cf-4f09-b81b-bb3e606edbe7"}
